label chapter7:

    # [Scene: Lumen Bay Boardwalk | Early Evening]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, ascending strings with a steady, hopeful rhythm]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Distant gulls, low murmur of departing neighbors, the slap of tide against pilings]
    "You remember the exact tremor in your throat when you finished speaking. It was the same small, human crack that always shows up when you try to make something that matters into words. But the crack"
    "didn't splinter the room; it reshaped it. People leaned in. You called for a vote — not on a slick corporate fix, but on the messy, stubborn work of restoring the marsh with town hands and"
    "town money."
    "You feel the salt on your lips, the bite of late sea air on your face. Your journal, weighted in your bag, presses against your ribs like a promise. Rosa is beside you, clipboard clasped to"
    "her chest; Asha’s grin is a live thing—more like a spark than a smile—and Jonah stands a step off, jaw tight but eyes bright."
    show rosa_mendes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_mendes "You did what needed to be said. The council heard it, Maya — we heard it. People are talking about sign-ups already."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "They will need concrete plans. Work crews, pay, materials. A clear line from donation to shovel. No one wants another promise that disappears into a spreadsheet."

    rosa_mendes "I've already texted three neighborhood captains. They'll run door-to-door. Mayor Durant wants a draft of the bylaws by Friday."
    show asha_patel at center:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_patel "Bylaws and battle songs. Perfect combination.' 'I'm going to start a seed workshop tonight. Bring that camera — we'll make evidence out of seedlings."
    "You swallow. It tastes like copper and hope. 'Yes. And we’ll pull the small grants together. Redirect them to paid crews so no one has to choose between rent and work.'"
    hide rosa_mendes
    show jonah_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "And the fishers are in. Me and the boys—early starts. We don't need cranes to move rocks when we have rope and people."
    "Dahlia Kestrel watches from across the promenade, a pale silhouette against the clinical glow of her team's tablets. Her face is unreadable — something you have learned to call 'complex' when you don't know whether her"
    "silence is calculation or concession. The salt air tastes like a promise that will need more than wish to keep."
    hide maya_reyes
    hide asha_patel
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch7_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: The strings lift a half-step — hopeful, not naive]
    show maya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "This town built itself with hands. We can rebuild it that way."
    # [Scene: Skyline Rooftop Garden | Night — Community Workshop]
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch7_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Voices and laughter, the steady scrape of trowels on soil]
    # [Smell: Compost warmth, wet cardboard, the tang of sea spray carried on the breeze]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Light, percussive motif — a rhythm matching the steady hand-work of planting]
    "You run a hand along a tray of cordgrass plugs and feel the soft give of damp roots. Asha organizes the volunteers with chirpy efficiency; Rosa negotiates a donation of watering cans from a grocer down"
    "the boardwalk. The rooftop hums — not with mechanical certainty, but with the unsteady, alive noise of people doing the next right thing."
    show asha_patel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_patel "Okay — small hands on the rim. Show them how to press the roots in, not jam them. Rhythm, Maya. Plant like you're singing the tide back."
    "You crouch, showing a child how to cup the soil. The kid giggles when a worm peeks out; you laugh with them, and the sound loosens something in your chest."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We’ll schedule rotating shifts. Paid. Skills training, too — tide reading, pump maintenance. If a storm comes, people need to be ready to act, not only watch."
    show rosa_mendes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_mendes "I've reworked the grant applications. If we can show payroll plus measurable restoration this quarter, the council will reallocate funds. It helps that the local paper ran that piece — more volunteers signed up this morning than I expected."

    asha_patel "And the Skyline garden will be our training ground — demonstration plots, living bylaws pinned to the shed door. People can see the mechanics."
    "You pin a tiny hand-written bylaw to the community board: 'Funds for restoration remain in municipal escrow, released by neighborhood committee vote.' The ink dries under the warmth of the bulbs and your chest grows lighter as if the letter itself can hold a promise."

    menu:
        "Teach the children's planting session":
            "You stay with the kids, teaching the planting rhythm, laughing when small hands get muddy. The children’s focused curiosity refuels you—practical wonder that anchors hope."
        "Double-check the reallocated grants spreadsheet":
            "You step inside the shed and spread the ledger across the table, cursor hovering over numbers. The slow arithmetic of funding steadies your nerves; you rearrange figures until community payrolls fit like puzzle pieces."

    # --- merge ---
    "..."
    # [Scene: Marsh of Tides (restoration site) | Dawn]
    hide asha_patel
    hide maya_reyes
    hide rosa_mendes

    scene bg ch7_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Spoons tapping on steel buckets, the low, constant chatter of people, gulls crying overhead]
    # [Smell: Rich, dark mud, seaweed, wet rope]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Steady crescendo of strings and soft percussion — a feeling of building momentum]
    "Elias Kwan shows up at first light, sweater sleeves rolled, rope coiled like a ritual around his waist. He arrives with a small crew of day-workers and young fishers who learned to read the water before"
    "they learned to read contracts. Elias Kwan’s hands are sure on the stones; he organizes placements with the economy of someone who has moved nets and boats all his life."
    show elias_kwan at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_kwan "Pass me that last revetment piece. Plant the cordgrass in the lower beds first — tide will carry the topsoil in two weeks if we don't anchor it."
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We’ll stagger the work so the pumps and the kitchens can share power. Jonah has a rotation for the younger crews."
    show jonah_reyes at center:
        zoom 0.7

    jonah_reyes "And coffee. Lots of coffee. You can lead the midday briefing — show the tide markers and how to patch a breach."

    elias_kwan "You keep those bylaws of yours close. Keep people earning while they learn."
    "Hands pass buckets. Asha calibrates a salvaged solar charger; someone hums a tune that used to belong to your father. The work is hard, and the muscles protest, but the ache feels like currency you are"
    "spending on something that might pay you back in windless mornings and roofs that don't leak."
    "You kneel by a newly planted trench, press mud against a plug, and imagine lines on a map becoming ridges on the land. The first time you feel the tide pull and the planted roots hold, something in your chest unclenches."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A distant rumble — an early squall, not yet a storm]
    hide elias_kwan
    hide maya_reyes
    hide jonah_reyes

    scene bg ch7_453e40_5 at full_bg
    "When the squall comes, it comes like a test. You stand with a small knot of people on the edge of a newly protected channel, rain dotting the surface like tiny coins. Water lifts, presses against"
    "the new revetment. For a long, suspended moment you watch as the surge hits — and the cordgrass, the stones, the living stitch of practice and sweat, hold."
    show asha_patel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_patel "Measurements! Read the gauges!"

    "Volunteer" "Level stable — two centimeters above baseline, no breach."
    show rosa_mendes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_mendes "Get that on the live stream. Get it on record."
    "Someone does. Your camera at your hip captures the water lapping and not taking. The clip goes out: raw, unslick, a grainy proof of what people can do. A local reporter calls it 'Lumen Bay's grassroots"
    "defense.' A small, genuine smile slips across your face — the kind that happens when you let yourself believe in a thing because it has just been proven."

    menu:
        "Walk the channel with Elias to check the placements":
            "You fall into step with Elias, shoulders wet, his breath visible. He points out an angle you missed; you adjust a stone together in companionable silence, and the simple teamwork folds you closer."
        "Run back to the rooftop to check the sensors and the payroll app":
            "You sprint across the boardwalk, mud ticking at your heels, and log the surge data into the payroll app so crews receive their day’s wage. The screen's confirmation tone is small salvation: 'Payment processed.'"

    # --- merge ---
    "..."
    # [Scene: Marsh of Tides | Later Morning — After the Squall]
    hide asha_patel
    hide rosa_mendes

    scene bg ch7_453e40_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Cheers, the clatter of reclaimed pumps, a reporter's voice narrating into a microphone]
    # [Smell: Wet wool, toasted coffee from a makeshift field kitchen, the sweet rot of disturbed peat]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Flourishing strings, brass hints — celebratory but intimate]
    "The town hums with a new rhythm. Kitchens that had hoarded salvaged pumps now run water for cleanup. Solar chargers hum on a tarp bench. Children who helped this morning sit with elders and compare tide"
    "marks, their small fingers tracing the same lines as weathered hands. Jonah tells a story about a net mended by three generations and everyone laughs at the punchline together."
    "You take your journal from your bag and write until the ink runs like a small map across the page: bylaws, payroll schedules, supply caches, volunteer rosters. Each line is both legalese and a litany — a way to turn goodwill into durable structure."
    show maya_reyes at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We’ll codify who holds the escrow, the threshold for spending, how votes are called in emergencies…"
    show rosa_mendes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_mendes "I'll bring it to council. The signatures from the captains will be enough to get a first reading."
    show asha_patel at center:
        zoom 0.7

    asha_patel "And I'll run the next training: pump repair and tide pattern workshops. We should document every method so the engineers can't call it anecdote."
    "Even some of AquaWorks’ engineers have been here — hovering at the edge, notebooks out. They nod at data, at the measurable reduction in settlement in the newly planted stretch. For a moment the gulf between"
    "corporate scale and communal care narrows into a practical conversation about soil permeability and root binding strength. It doesn't erase the difference in value systems, but it proves what you've been saying: local knowledge and local"
    "labor can deliver results."
    hide maya_reyes
    show elias_kwan at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_kwan "We didn't need their cranes. We needed hands that know tide and time. That's not against progress — it's progress that remembers where it came from."
    hide rosa_mendes
    show maya_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_reyes "We need both: skills, money, and the wisdom to choose what stays. For now, this is ours."
    "For a few weeks the rise is real. You sleep in a bed that feels lighter because people are awake and doing. The media runs pieces that call the town a model of grassroots resilience; volunteers"
    "come from nearby towns to learn. You allow yourself to imagine the marsh as a defense built from memory and muscle rather than a screen of steel."
    hide asha_patel
    hide elias_kwan
    hide maya_reyes

    scene bg ch7_453e40_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sustained, warm chord]
    "You sit for a moment, hands muddy, heart steadier than it has been in months. The work ahead is long; you know that every tide will bring its own lesson. But the energy in the town"
    "is no longer only reaction; it has texture: patchwork competence, shared jokes, inventory lists turned into stories."
    "You trace the page with your thumb and write one last line for now: 'Community-led restoration as primary defense — voted by neighborhood councils.' The ink is not a declaration of victory, only a promise you can show people and hold them to."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A gentle, ascending motif that invites forward motion]
    "You close the journal and for a breath — a single, honest breath — you let yourself hope. The tide recedes, and behind it, something is left: not a finished fortress, but a rhythm of repair."
    "You can feel the next choices pressing close — more tactics, more votes, more negotiations — but for now, the town is awake, and its hands are moving."

    scene bg ch7_453e40_9 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Hopeful swell, then a poised, anticipatory silence]

    scene bg ch7_453e40_10 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

